Personally I wouldn't use a champagne yeast, it's going to give you some
flavors that aren't really appropriate for a beer.  It's also not really
necessary.  There used to be a school of thought that beer yeast wasn't
capable of higher ABV fermentations (it may have been true at some point
in the past), but it's not really the case today.  I would guess that
the recipe you found is a fairly old one, or written by a brewer with
some outdated information.

IMO, any general beer yeast should do fine.  Nottingham is a pretty
popular choice as a dry yeast for ales in general.  The Safale options
would probably work fine as well.

Assuming the amber is LME and you're making a 5 gallon batch, you're going
to end up with an OG around 1.100 or so.  IMO, you will definitely want to
make sure you aerate really well and probably pitch a couple packets of
dry yeast (they're fairly cheap).  Ideally, you could make a regular beer
and then use the sediment from that fermentation to pitch in to your
barleywine.  That should give you a really large/healthy yeast population.

John.
